        about: '3D modelling is topological problem-solving — you are controlling how triangles connect on a surface to produce a shape. Hard surface and organic modelling are two fundamentally different workflows, and knowing which to use is half the battle. Hard surface (machines, furniture, architecture) uses boolean operations, bevels, and precise edge placement. Organic modelling (characters, creatures, natural forms) uses Subdivision Surface and sculpting tools that round and smooth geometry.\n\nAt this level you also learn modifiers — non-destructive operations that live on top of the mesh. The Mirror modifier halves your work on any symmetrical model. The Array modifier handles repetition. Working non-destructively means you can adjust settings at any point without losing work.',
